osition of global leadership will face challenges in the future, as it has in other realms of international competition. American Universities in a Global Market addresses the variety of issues crucial to understanding this preeminence and this challenge. The book examines the various factors that contributed to America’s success in higher education, including openness to people and ideas, generous governmental support, and a tradition of decentralized friendly competition. It also explores the advantages of holding a dominant position in this marketplace and examines the current state of American higher education in a comparative context, placing particular emphasis on how market forces affect universities. By discussing the differences in quality among students and institutions around the world, this volume sheds light on the singular aspects of American higher education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCompetition, International. 0aEducation and globalization. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aAdams, James D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBettinger, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlack, Grant C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorghans, Lex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBound, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClotfelter, Charles T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClotfelter, Charles T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCörvers, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Richard B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul